title: Herring Point Five and Dime runs by Biden Center, but will Joe run in 2016?
text:
Herring Point Five and Dime runs by Biden Center, but will Joe run in 2016? Brock Diaz, 14, wins 10K By Dave Frederick | Oct 20, 2015 Photo by: Dave Frederick Ricky "Pretty In Pink" Ward runs with his sons A.J. and Austin. 
The second annual Herring Point 5K and 10K run Oct. 17, welcomed a small field of runners to a beautiful course on a picture perfect fall morning at Cape Henlopen State Park. 
The race started and finished at the top of the Great Dune overlooking the Naval Jetty and ran past the Biden Center twice, raising the question “will Joe run in 2016?” 
Matt Littlejohn, 30, of Cambridge, Md., was the 5K winner in 19:26. David Griffin, 54, from Westminster, Md., was second and top male masters runner in 20:57. 
Jeanne Knowles, 24, of Lewes was the top female and third overall in a time of 21:29. Merrilee Seidman, 61, from Alexandria, Va., was top female masters 24:18. 
Ricky Ward of Milton, running his first 5K on his 50th birthday, ran 31:55. His sons Austin Brooks, 19, 36:07 and A.J. Brooks, 28, 37:01 joined dad for the first time running celebration. 
The 10K double loop race was won by 14-year-old Brock Diaz of Lewes who negotiated the race distance for the first time in 45:20. Brock is a freshman on the Sussex Academy cross country team. 
Susan Dunn, 38, former Delmar Wildcat field hockey player, was the overall women’s winner in 46:17. 
Todd Birely, 48, was the top male masters runner in 48:17. 
Linda Schwartz-Chi, 50, was top in female masters 53:25. 
The inaugural Paradise “Crush Cancer” 5K run/walk Oct. 19 had a field of 160 runners. 
Martin Rodriguez, 33, of Selbyville was the overall winner in 17:45. Chris Stanley, 46, the UPS man from Fruitland, Md., was top masters in 19:30. 
Tricia Gilson, 28, from Lewes was first female in 22:17. Kimberly Nuttall, 46, of Millsboro was top female masters 25:54. 
The next Seashore Striders race is the 26th annual Seawitch Fall 5K Classic Oct. 18, beginning at 9 a.m. at Grove Park in Rehoboth. 
The upcoming Rehoboth Beach Seashore Marathon & Half Marathon is Saturday, Dec. 5 at 7 a.m. 
If you enter the marathon now, the fee is $140. Total limit on entries is 2,900 runners. Register online at seashorestriders.com . Matt Littlejohn, the 5K winner, leads runners on the trail. (Photo by: Dave Frederick ) Jeanne Knowles was the first female to finish in the 5K in 21:29. (Photo by: Dave Frederick ) Do not attempt to apprehend this runner yourself, but call your nearest FBI office. Jack Vassalotti.
